European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley — — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people once thought like that, but now it's not possible anymore, because it's clearly become a crisis of the eurozone.
To deal with it is both easier and more difficult than usually anticipated.
The economic logic of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all of the above three areas.
Although the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to go through a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation enhances export competitiveness, which means using external demand to compensate for internal demand.
However, these countries are all members of the eurozone and do not have independent currencies to devalue, so they can only use internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made considerable efforts to tighten their belts.
But there is one economic variable that has not changed along with the adjustment of other variables, which is the debt of the public and private sectors.
The face value of government accumulated debt has not changed, bank debt — — except for some debt owed to junior creditors, has also remained largely unchanged.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy in a contradictory situation: the heavier the reduction of wages and other costs, the heavier the relative burden of accumulated debt.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased to meet the debt of the government and its supporters (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal devaluation strategy to take effect, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the face value of debt.
The government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity; when banks are insolvent, the debt should be written off.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
Policy makers are reluctant to take this path, and this is understandable.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is worried about losing the trust of the financial market.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs will only burden other countries.
These concerns cannot be said to be without reason, but one should not draw unreasonable conclusions from them.
The only way out is two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European country leaders must choose one of the two.
They all ruled out the path of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
To deny this is both illogical and unreasonable.
The operation of debt restructuring is simple and clear.
The government can issue a batch of new debt instruments with face values discounted by a certain proportion from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose between two options: either hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value, but with a later maturity date and a lower interest rate; or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value, but with an earlier maturity date and a higher interest rate.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it work, there are three prerequisites.
The first is to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone has to guarantee this batch of bonds.
In the 1980s, during the Latin American debt restructuring under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "guarantee big brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will raise expectations for other countries, leading to contagion effects.
Finally, the balance sheets of banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must be strengthened.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the mere formality that was done earlier this year.
If debt restructuring implies capital inadequacy, then a comprehensive debt-for-equity swap must be carried out for the relevant banks.
If that is not enough, the government must step in and inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires consistent action by all countries.
Once the banks' balance sheets are strengthened, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debt without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
The leaders of Germany must acknowledge that the country's banks have a significant risk exposure to the debt of peripheral countries in the eurozone, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince their backroom bosses and voters that guaranteeing debt restructuring and bank recapitalization with public funds is a necessary condition for the internal devaluation strategy; since Germany has urged other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should take on the responsibility of guaranteeing it without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe — — without doing so, they will face great danger.
Because that is the reality.
